This course gives students the opportunity to participate in the production of a feature-length fiction film. Students engage in all aspects of production, including: screenplay writing, production design, cinematography, production sound, acting, and directing. &#8232;&#8232;

Students thought that this course was \"excellent\" and \"a lot of fun,\" with some calling it one of their \"favorite classes\" taken at Penn. Although most thought the course was \"enjoyable\" and \"wonderful,\" some were \"disappointed,\" describing the class as \"disorganized\" and in need of \"more structure.\"&#8232;&#8232;

Students described Professor Messaris as \"great,\" \"excellent,\" and \"amazing.\" However, students also criticized his lack of cohesion for this course.&#8232;

Students felt that the course had an \"uneven work load.\" They found the shoots to be \"sometimes disorganized,\" and that the inexperienced students often ended up with \"unsuccessful shoots\" because of a lack of organization. The course is intended as a follow-up to COMM 140, Film Forms and Contexts, and COMM 262, Visual Communication. Students who have not taken either of those courses should consult with the instructor before enrolling. COMM 241 is followed by COMM 242. Students may enroll in either or both.

This course explores the theory, research and application of the persuasive effects of communication in social and mass contexts. The primary focus is on the effects of messages on attitudes, opinions, values, and behaviors. Applications of theories learned in the course include political, commercial, and public service advertising; propaganda; and communication campaigns (e.g. anti-smoking).&#8232;&#8232;
The students reported a “cohesive and engaging curriculum” that showed a “different way to view mass communication”. The course also “offered a strong theory base but also had assignments that used the theory in a practical way”. Students seemed to enjoy the link that the class had to current events, which were highlighted both before and during lectures. &#8232;&#8232;
Most students liked Professor Cappella and his teaching style. “Dr. Cappella is a great professor. I enjoyed the class very much. He is very up to date in terms of technology, news, and material presented in class,” said one student. Other students reported that Professor Cappella is knowledgeable about the subject matter and has a good working relationship with the TAs in the course. Some students, however, felt that Professor Cappella sped through class slides, glossed over material, and was somewhat boring during lectures. In general, however, both the professor and the TAs were accessible throughout the semester, and they complemented each other and the lectures well.&#8232;&#8232;
The course consists of readings, exams, and a final “Public Service Announcement” project. The workload is significant, and the exams were reportedly difficult. The major PSA assignment had mostly positive reviews. One student describe it as “challenging but very helpful in terms of knowledge gained.” The project consists of two sections due at different times during the semester and was “very time consuming and overwhelming.”

This course is designed to explore the unique issues that arise for communications researchers who work with children. The class begins by considering the role of theory in designing research, then reviews the major methodological approaches, and finally examines the variety of contexts in which such research is employed. The course considers the unique ethical issues and protective mechanisms in place. The course culminates in group-based, supervised research wherein students have an opportunity to design and implement a child-focused study. &#8232;
&#8232;Students reported that the course was one of “the most useful and well-taught” they had taken at Penn. Although it “was a good course overall”, some students reported difficulty having no prior research class experience.&#8232;&#8232;
The course was co-taught. Students wrote that Professor Linebarger was “a sweetheart” and a “great teacher,” but many found her “not very organized” overall.&#8232; One student wrote, “I especially enjoyed the balance between [the two] personalities, [they] both complement each other as instructors” while another wrote it “hindered my learning experience…too many conflicting styles of teaching.”
Students said the exams were hard with one student mentioning that material they were tested on was “too trivial.” The course culminated in a final project, which included a significant time of prep-work and execution time.
